---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="tips · wanderlust"
  description="General travel tips I reuse on every trip: insurance, forex cards, and what I pack."
>
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-2xl">
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl font-medium leading-[1.05] tracking-tight md:text-5xl">
      Things I do on every trip.
    </h1>
  </section>

  <aside class="mx-auto mt-8 max-w-2xl border-l-2 pl-6 py-2" style="border-color: var(--color-accent)">
    <p class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest" style="color: var(--color-accent)">
      Note
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed">
      Personal preferences, nothing sponsored. The cards and services named here
      are just what I use.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <div class="prose-trip mt-12">
    <h2 id="seasons">Timing and seasons</h2>

    <p>
      Check the season before you lock in dates, and lean towards the shoulder
      season where you can. You dodge the worst of the crowds and the peak prices
      while the weather is still good and most things are open. Off-season isn't
      off-limits either: some places are perfectly fine and a lot cheaper, just
      confirm that what you actually want to do isn't shut for the monsoon or low
      season. Each itinerary here lists a best season to start from.
    </p>

    <h2 id="insurance">Travel insurance</h2>

    <p>
      I take travel insurance on every trip, regardless of destination. It's
      cheap against the cost of the trip and covers what actually derails
      travel: medical emergencies, cancellations, delays, and lost baggage. Some
      visas require it anyway (Schengen, for one), but I buy it even where it
      isn't mandatory.
    </p>

    <h2 id="cards">Forex cards</h2>

    <p>
      For spending abroad I use a <strong>Scapia</strong> credit card. Zero forex
      markup is the whole reason I carry it, and it's my go-to travelling abroad.
      I sometimes put spends on <strong>HDFC Infinia</strong> instead, since the
      cashback usually covers the markup and then some.
    </p>

    <p>
      As a prepaid backup I've used a <strong>BookMyForex</strong> forex card. I
      also had a <strong>Niyo</strong> card, but it failed to work on a few trips
      so I eventually closed it. Their travel community on social media is active
      and worth a follow, though.
    </p>

    <h2 id="cash">Cash</h2>

    <p>
      Always carry some US dollars, or another widely accepted currency. They
      exchange easily almost everywhere, whereas Indian rupees are sometimes not
      accepted at all, and where they are the rate is usually bad. I keep dollars
      as backup and change them locally as needed.
    </p>

    <h2 id="food">Food from home</h2>

    <p>
      Vegetarian options thin out in a lot of places, so I travel with backup
      food. It also saves money in expensive destinations, where a single meal
      can run upwards of 2,000 INR. Ready-to-eat packs work well, both the
      just-add-hot-water and the just-reheat kinds. Thepla is the classic, it keeps for days without
      refrigeration, and dry snacks like bhel puri travel well too. Fruit, bread,
      and drinks are easy to find almost everywhere, so it's mainly proper meals
      you need to plan for.
    </p>

    <h2 id="adapter">Universal adapter</h2>

    <p>
      Carry a universal travel adapter, always. Plug types vary country to
      country, and one universal adapter saves hunting for the right plug after
      you land.
    </p>
  </div>
</Layout>
